Sentiment Analysis

As a brief summary of sentiment analysis, a condensed workflow will be to source material, stem the tokens if using only words, remove stop words, and perform lookups on lexicons to establish sentiment of the word. From there, grouping, presenting, and visualizing the data is up to the coder.
Sentiment Analysis references a corpus, which is to say source material, and a lexicon, which is a library of words with associated ratings for numeric values or binary positive/negative values. Most of the work will be on cleaning the corpus. In this assignment, we will be comparing four lexicons; afinn, nrc, bing, and syuzhet. Another of interest would be VADER, referenced later.

From here, we want to clean our data by the tidytext principles using code sourced from Text Mining with R (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.2).

tidyHuck <- huckleberry[-(1:384),] %>% #removing first 380 rows since its an index and interferes with chapter regex
  mutate(
    linenumber = row_number(), #add index of row numbers
    chapter = cumsum(str_detect(text,  #add index of chapter
                                regex("CHAPTER ([IVXLC]*\\.|THE LAST)", #by finding any text starting with "chapter #"
                                      ignore_case = TRUE)))) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text) #notice we use 'word' as the unit of token


paged_table(tidyHuck)
#Book Copy for use in unnest_tokens by regex
tidy_books <- austen_books() %>%
  group_by(book) %>%
  mutate(
    linenumber = row_number(),
    chapter = cumsum(str_detect(text, 
                                regex("^chapter [\\divxlc]", 
                                      ignore_case = TRUE)))) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)


Lexicon Sentiment Tests

To get familiar with the package and lexicons, first we will perform a few exercises with some of the lexicons and the tidytext package.


NRC

A look at the most commonly used words with joy from the NRC lexicon (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.2). The NRC Lexicon has categories for the words such as joy,anger, or trust. This is quite useful for capturing types of emotions.


paged_table(get_sentiments("nrc"))
nrc_joy <- get_sentiments("nrc") %>%

Bing

The bing lexicon is a simple binary label that identifies whether a word is positive or negative. In the example below, we also divide our lines up into chunks of 80 words and compare the positive to negative counts to get an idea of the text as a whole (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.2)


paged_table(get_sentiments("bing"))
huckSentiment <- tidyHuck %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>% #join words that match bing lexicon
  count(index = linenumber %/% 80, sentiment) %>% #Removed 'book' as initial argument since we are only working with one book
  pivot_wider(names_from = sentiment, values_from = n, values_fill = 0) %>% 
  mutate(sentiment = positive - negative)
paged_table(huckSentiment)


ggplot(huckSentiment, aes(index, sentiment)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE)


We can see that there is quite a variance in Huckleberry Finn. I would imagine this is natural for fiction works and could be an indicator of entertaining reads.

From here, lets check the four different lexicons to compare with.

Lexicon Comparisons

AFINN

Here we introduce the afinn lexicon, which provides numeric values between -5 and 5 (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.3)


afinn2 <- get_sentiments(c("afinn"))
unique(afinn2$value)
##  [1] -2 -3  2  1 -1  3  4 -4 -5  5  0
#Create tibble for AFINN values
afinn <- tidyHuck %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>% #look up sentiment
  group_by(index = linenumber %/% 80) %>% #chunk by 80 lines
  summarise(sentiment = sum(value)) %>% #count values by our groups
  mutate(method = "AFINN") #label the lexicon used

bing_and_nrc <- bind_rows(
  tidyHuck %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
    mutate(method = "Bing et al."),
  tidyHuck %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc") %>% 
                 filter(sentiment %in% c("positive", 
                                         "negative"))#only grab the positive and negative qualities in NRC and avoid anger, joy, etc.
    ) %>%
    mutate(method = "NRC")) %>%
  count(method, index = linenumber %/% 80, sentiment) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = sentiment,
              values_from = n,
              values_fill = 0) %>% #pivot wider to easily subtract the positive count from the negative count
  mutate(sentiment = positive - negative)#create overall sentiment value for the group
paged_table(afinn)
paged_table(bing_and_nrc)


Syuzhet

Our last lexicon requires the installation and use of a package called syuzhet. The main difference between this package and others is that ratings have more nuanced values than the other lexicons which are; 1.0, 0.8 0.75, 0.6, 0.5, 0.4, 0.25, 0.1, 0.25, 0.4, 0.5, 0.6, 0.75, 0.8, 1.0.


The syuzhet lexicon has come under criticism, particularly by Swaffored but still holds value and is extremely popular.

Another package of interest is VADER, which is a lexicon that performs particularly well on social media. You can use its github page and paper for more resources. If one of the links above is not working, try a search with the title of the paper VADER: A Parsimonious Rule-based Model for Sentiment Analysis of Social Media Text by C.J. Hutto and Eric Gilbert.
value <- get_sentiment(tidyHuck$word,method = "syuzhet") #calling syuzhet's get_sentiment command

syuzhetHuck <- cbind(tidyHuck,value) #attaching to tidyHuck to match AFINN's tibble structure


#Below code finishes matching AFINN structure
syuzhet <- syuzhetHuck %>% 
  group_by(index = linenumber %/% 80) %>% #Re-iterating AFINN's 80 word division for comparison
  summarise(sentiment = sum(value)) %>% 
  mutate(method = "syuzhet")


Lets see how they all compare against each other visually (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.3). 

bind_rows(afinn, 
          bing_and_nrc,syuzhet) %>%
  ggplot(aes(index, sentiment, fill = method)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~method, ncol = 1, scales = "free_y")


Overall, it looks like syuzhet would be most similar to AFINN or NRC. The syuzhet lexicon doesnt seem to be as sensitive to slightly negative words but still captures anything overly negative.

To match this with the syuzhet package, we will need to classify our words into positive or negative and filter out any neutrals.

syuzhetHuckSentiment <- syuzhetHuck %>% mutate(sentiment =
  if_else(value > 0,'positive', 
    if_else(value < 0,'negative','neutral')
  )
) #Classify our values

syuzhet_word_counts <- syuzhetHuckSentiment %>% #count
  count(word, sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>%
  ungroup()

syuzhetHuckLookup <- syuzhetHuckSentiment %>% #create lookup to join word values for display
  select(word,value,sentiment)

syuzhetHuckLookup <- unique(syuzhetHuckLookup)#remove repeats


syuzhetCounts <-left_join(syuzhet_word_counts[,c("word","n")],syuzhetHuckLookup, by = "word") #performing left join to show value of words with our counts to give reader idea of weight

nonNeutralSyuzhetCounts<- syuzhetCounts %>%
  filter(sentiment != 'neutral') %>% #filter out neutral words, value 0
  mutate(method = 'syuzhet')


paged_table(nonNeutralSyuzhetCounts)


Now that we have these counts, it is easy to compare visually (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.4).

bing_word_counts %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sentiment, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(x = "Contribution to sentiment",
       y = NULL)


Using bing, we can highlight heavily impacting words. From this perspective, one could deduce that the word well may be overly used as a filler word when speaking due to the dialect that Mark Twain wrote the book in. Combining both into a grid allows a comparison. Surprisingly, syuzhet captures the word warnt and has no value for the word dark or miss.


bing_word_counts <- bing_word_counts %>%
  mutate(method='bing')

bind_rows(bing_word_counts,nonNeutralSyuzhetCounts) %>%
  group_by(method,sentiment) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 5) %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n,word, fill = method)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_grid(sentiment~method)


Custom Stop Words

We can see from bing and syuzhet, that the word well is identified as a positive word, but due to the dialect its more likely Twain inserted the word as a filler word. We can easily remove this through the use of custom stop words (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.4). With this lexicon, we could then filter with the created tibble as below.
custom_stop_words <- bind_rows(tibble(word = c("well"),  
                                      lexicon = c("custom")), 
                               stop_words)
paged_table(custom_stop_words)

Word Clouds

A word cloud is an effective way to view most used words and can be thought of a plot unto itself. Using a stop words list, we can highlight important most used words (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.5).
tidyHuck %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%
  count(word) %>%
  with(wordcloud(word, n, min.freq = 50))



We can also view both negative and positive words in the same plot with the use of reshapes comparison cloud and acast (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.5).


tidyHuck %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
  count(word, sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>%
  acast(word ~ sentiment, value.var = "n", fill = 0) %>%
  comparison.cloud(colors = c("gray20", "gray80"),
                   max.words = 100)

Units Larger than Single Words

Handling negation is an important aspect of sentiment analysis, as without it, inaccurate values or representation may happen. We can accomodate this by using sentences as the token (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.6).
huckSentences <- tibble(text = huckleberry$text) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(sentence, text, token = "sentences")

huckSentences$sentence[111]
## [1] "the doctor.uncle silas.sister hotchkiss.aunt sally in trouble."


Another option is to chunk the text by chapters using a regex pattern inside the unnest_tokens function (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.6). Be very careful! This took me a minute to figure out and troubleshoot as I was getting thousands of Huckleberry Finn chapters despite my regex being correct. I made some notes inside my code on how I worked out the bugs. This required to work with the raw text and not the tidytext we formatted at the beginning.


#Notes on unnest_tokens(chapter,text,token = regex, pattern)
# To have this work in a legible manner, you have to make sure that you group by book before summarising, which requires a 'book' column next to the 'text' column. Make sure you're regex is correct and remove any excess lines like indexes/prefaces


#Prepping Huck text to format well
huckText <- as_tibble(huckleberry$text[-(1:384)]) #Removing first 384 lines to avoid regex confusion and preface to book
colnames(huckText)[1] <- 'text'
huckText <- huckText %>% mutate(book = 'Huckleberry')



## Altered Code to only have both books
austen_chapters <- austen_books() %>%
  filter(book == 'Sense & Sensibility') %>%
  rbind(huckText)%>%
  group_by(book)%>%
  unnest_tokens(chapter, text, token = "regex", 
                pattern = "CHAPTER ([IVXLC]*\\.|THE LAST|[\\dIVXLC])") %>%
  ungroup()

##Single book
huckChapters <- huckText %>% 
  group_by(book) %>%
  unnest_tokens(chapter, text, token = "regex", 
                pattern = "CHAPTER ([IVXLC]*\\.|THE LAST|[\\dIVXLC])") %>%
  ungroup()

We can also use this method to find the most negative chapters in a book by joining with our negative sentiments (Silge, J., & Robinson, D. 2017, Sec. 2.6).
#Bing Chapter Negativity
bingnegative <- get_sentiments("bing") %>% 
  filter(sentiment == "negative")

wordcounts <- tidyHuck %>%
  group_by(chapter) %>%
  summarize(words = n())
paged_table(wordcounts)
#Chapter Sentiment
tidyHuck %>%
  semi_join(bingnegative) %>% #join/filter for negative word matches
  group_by(chapter) %>%
  summarize(negativewords = n()) %>%
  left_join(wordcounts, by = c( "chapter")) %>%
  mutate(ratio = negativewords/words) %>%
  filter(chapter != 0) %>%
  slice_max(ratio, n = 1) %>%  #show only most negative
  ungroup()
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   chapter negativewords words  ratio
##     <int>         <int> <int>  <dbl>
## 1      13            76  2059 0.0369



Lets compare this with the Syuzhet lexicon. We will do this using just the ratio as Bing did, but well also look at including the numerical score that Syuzhet offers.


syuzhetNegative <- nonNeutralSyuzhetCounts %>%
  filter(sentiment == "negative")

wordcounts <- tidyHuck %>%
  group_by(chapter) %>%
  summarize(words = n())
paged_table(wordcounts)
#Chapter Sentiment
tidyHuck %>%
  semi_join(syuzhetNegative) %>% #join/filter for negative word matches
  group_by(chapter) %>%
  summarize(negativewords = n()) %>%
  left_join(wordcounts, by = c( "chapter")) %>% #pulls word count sum to create ratio
  mutate(ratio = negativewords/words) %>%
  filter(chapter != 0) %>%
  slice_max(ratio, n = 1) %>%  #show only most negative
  ungroup()
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   chapter negativewords words  ratio
##     <int>         <int> <int>  <dbl>
## 1      22           112  2075 0.0540
# Negative Score
negativeChapters <- tidyHuck %>%
  semi_join(syuzhetNegative) %>% #join/filter for negative word matches
  group_by(chapter) %>%
  left_join(syuzhetHuckLookup) %>%
  group_by(chapter) %>%
  summarize(score = sum(value)) %>%
  arrange(score)
paged_table(negativeChapters)


By ratio, it looks like chapter 22 has the highest ratio of negative words at a .053 ratio (112 words) which is relatively higher than Bings ratio of Chapter 13 at .036 (76 words).
If we look at Syuzhets negative sum, one would judge that Chapter 18 would be the most negative chapter at a total of -109.10 score. This doesnt account for any positive words to balance it out though. Lets add those as well.
syuzhetPositive <- nonNeutralSyuzhetCounts %>%
  filter(sentiment == "positive")



syuzhetNeutral <- syuzhetCounts %>%
  filter(sentiment == 'neutral')

tidyHuck %>%
  semi_join(syuzhetPositive) %>% #join/filter for negative word matches
  group_by(chapter) %>%
  summarize(positivewords = n()) %>%
  left_join(wordcounts, by = c( "chapter")) %>% #pulls word count sum to create ratio
  mutate(ratio = positivewords/words) %>%
  filter(chapter != 0) %>%
  slice_max(ratio, n = 1) %>%  #show only most negative
  ungroup()
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   chapter positivewords words  ratio
##     <int>         <int> <int>  <dbl>
## 1      25           189  2878 0.0657
# Positive Score
tidyHuck %>%
  semi_join(syuzhetPositive) %>% #join/filter for negative word matches
  group_by(chapter) %>%
  left_join(syuzhetHuckLookup) %>%
  group_by(chapter) %>%
  summarize(score = sum(value)) %>%
  arrange(desc(score)) %>%
  left_join(negativeChapters, by = 'chapter') %>%
  mutate(netScore = score.x + score.y) %>%
  arrange(netScore)
## # A tibble: 43  4
##    chapter score.x score.y netScore
##      <int>   <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>

##  2       6    58.4   -72.0   -13.5 
##  3      13    53.3   -60.3    -7.00
##  4      31    99.0  -104.     -4.75

Finally we can compare the two for a net score and it looks like Chapter 2 could be considered the most negative!

Conclusion

Sentiment Analysis is quite powerful and flexible depending on the lexicons you use. There is quite an art to it as many techniques or decisions in which words to include, how to include context, accounting for negative, and the arguable nature of a quantitative value for emotions are subject to the viewer. Overall, Sentiment Analysis is quite fun and I hope you learned a few new tricks.
